I never could tell but what it was only becau&s;e he
was my own. And I'm &s;o afraid of behaving like
a blind old goo&s;e, that I often &s;nub Hal, when he's
no more to blame than I am my&s;elf, for fear of his
getting out of my hands, and behaving like a cer|tain
young man he has been brought up with, and
who, I a&s;&s;ure you, de&s;erves to have his ears cropt
ten times a day, for one piece of impudence or
other. I &s;hould not have been &s;orry if he'd fallen
into the water along with that old lord, whom I
don't wi&s;h much good to neither; for, between
