perhaps, for the moment, require the mo&s;t &s;evere di&s;|play
of &s;elf-command, to di&s;gui&s;e, under the &s;em|blance
of good humour or indifference, the di&s;appoint|ment
they experience in them&s;elves, or the contempt
with which they are &s;eized for the changing multitude.</P>
<P>Mrs. Berlinton, though &s;he felt no re&s;entment
again&s;t Camilla for the de&s;ertion &s;he had occa&s;ioned
her, felt much &s;urprize; not to be fir&s;t was new to
her: and whoever, in any &s;tation of life, any cla&s;s of
