an unju&s;tifiable and dangerous levity, which irre&s;i&s;ta|bly
led him to treat with mockery and trifling the mo&s;t
&s;erious &s;ubjects. The puni&s;hment, however, which
he had now drawn upon him&s;elf would yet, he hoped,
touch his heart.</P>
<P>But the debts called debts of honour, met not with
&s;imilar treatment. He an&s;wered with &s;pirited re&s;ent|ment
demands he deemed highly flagitious, coun&s;elling
tho&s;e who &s;ent them, when next they applied to an un|happy
family to who&s;e calamities they had contribut|ed,
to enquire fir&s;t if its principles, as well as its
fortune, made the hazards of gaming among&s;t its do|me&s;tic
re&s;pon&s;ibilities.</P>
